🔹 Problem: Two Sum
Given an array nums and a target, return indices of two numbers such that:
nums[i] + nums[j] = target

🧠 1. Brute Force Approach
💡 Idea:

Check every pair.

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n²)
Space: O(1)

✅ Code (C++):
vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
    int n = nums.size();
    for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
        for(int j = i + 1; j < n; j++) {
            if(nums[i] + nums[j] == target) {
                return {i, j};
            }
        }
    }
    return {};
}

❌ Cons:
Very slow for large inputs
Not scalable (fails for n ≥ 10⁵)
Only useful as a starting point

📌 When to use:
Explaining the baseline in the interview
Very small arrays

⚡ 2. Better Approach (Sorting + Two Pointers)
💡 Idea:

Sort the array, then use two pointers.

⚠️ Problem: Sorting changes indices → must store original indices.

✅ Code:
vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
    vector<pair<int,int>> arr;
    for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        arr.push_back({nums[i], i});
    }

    sort(arr.begin(), arr.end());

    int left = 0, right = arr.size() - 1;

    while(left < right) {
        int sum = arr[left].first + arr[right].first;

        if(sum == target) {
            return {arr[left].second, arr[right].second};
        }
        else if(sum < target) left++;
        else right--;
    }

    return {};
}
⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n log n)
Space: O(n)
❌ Cons:
Loses original order → need extra structure
Not ideal if indices must be returned (extra work)
Slower than optimal
Modifies data (if not copied)
📌 When to use:
When an array can be sorted
When you don’t care about the original order
Useful stepping stone in interview

🚀 3. Optimal Approach (Hash Map)
💡 Idea:

Store numbers and their indices while traversing.

👉 For each element:

Check if (target - num) already exists

✅ Code:
vector<int> twoSum(vector<int>& nums, int target) {
    unordered_map<int, int> mp; // value -> index

    for(int i = 0; i < nums.size(); i++) {
        int complement = target - nums[i];

        if(mp.count(complement)) {
            return {mp[complement], i};
        }

        mp[nums[i]] = i;
    }

    return {};
}

⏱ Complexity:
Time: O(n)
Space: O(n)

❌ Cons:
Extra memory required
Hash collisions (rare but theoretical worst-case O(n²))
Not suitable if memory is strictly limited

📌 When to use:
Best choice in interviews
Large datasets
Need indices quickly
